# Deploying a New Page to philippeollivier.github.io

This file documents how to create and deploy a new page (e.g., `/nz-trip`) to the website.

## Overview

The site uses **Astro** with file-based routing. Any `.astro` file in `src/pages/` automatically becomes a route:
- `src/pages/index.astro` → `/`
- `src/pages/about.astro` → `/about`
- `src/pages/nz_trip/index.astro` → `/nz_trip` or `/nz-trip` (Astro normalizes underscores)

## Steps to Create a New Page

### 1. Create the Page File

Create a new Astro file in this directory:

**File:** `src/pages/nz_trip/index.astro`

```astro
---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="NZ Trip | Philippe Ollivier">
  <div class="container">
    <!-- Page content here -->
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Scoped styles - only apply to this page */
  .container {
    padding: 2rem;
    max-width: 1200px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
</style>
```

### 2. Add Page Content

Include:
- Images: place in `public/images/` and reference as `/images/filename`
- Videos: embed from YouTube/Vimeo using iframe (or use `<VideoEmbed />` component if available)
- Text: use semantic HTML (headings, paragraphs, sections)
- Custom components: create reusable UI components in `src/components/`

### 3. Style Your Page

#### Option A: Scoped Styles (Recommended)
Add `<style>` block at the bottom of your `.astro` file. Styles are automatically scoped to that page.

```astro
<style>
  h1 {
    color: #d33682; /* solarized red */
    font-family: 'Redaction 50 Bold'; /* matches site theme */
  }
</style>
```

#### Option B: Tailwind Classes
If you prefer utility classes, use Tailwind:

```astro
<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-red-600 mb-4">Heading</h1>
<p class="text-base leading-relaxed">Content</p>
```

#### Option C: Global Styles
Add styles to `src/styles/global.css` for site-wide rules (use sparingly).

### 4. Add Navigation (Optional)

To link from the home page or other pages to `/nz-trip`:

```astro
<a href="/nz_trip">Visit NZ Trip</a>
```

Astro will handle the routing automatically.

### 5. Add Images/Assets

1. Place image files in `public/images/`
2. Reference in your page:

```astro
<img src="/images/nz-photo.jpg" alt="Description" />
```

For optimized images with Astro's Image component:

```astro
---
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import nzPhoto from '../images/nz-photo.jpg';
---

<Image src={nzPhoto} alt="Description" />
```

### 6. Test Locally

```bash
npm run dev
```

Visit `http://localhost:3000/nz_trip` in your browser.

### 7. Deploy

Once you're satisfied with the page:

```bash
git add src/pages/nz_trip/
git add public/images/  # if you added new images
git commit -m "Add NZ trip page"
git push origin main
```

GitHub Actions will automatically:
1. Build the site
2. Deploy to GitHub Pages
3. Make the page live at `https://philippeollivier.github.io/nz-trip`

The deployment takes ~1-2 minutes. Check progress in the **Actions** tab on GitHub.

## File Structure Reference

```
src/pages/nz_trip/
├── index.astro           # Main page file (becomes /nz_trip route)
├── nz_trip.claude        # This file
└── (other .astro files)  # Nested routes: /nz_trip/sub-page, etc.

public/images/
├── nz-photo-1.jpg
├── nz-photo-2.jpg
└── ...
```

## Design Tips

- **Maintain consistency**: Use colors and fonts from `src/styles/global.css` (Solarized theme)
- **Mobile-first**: Test on mobile devices; use responsive classes or media queries
- **Performance**: Compress images to <1MB each; use WebP format when possible
- **Accessibility**: Add `alt` text to all images, use semantic HTML

## Page Transitions

The site uses Astro view transitions for smooth page navigation. To enable transitions on your page, wrap content in a transition div:

```astro
<div transition:animate={{ forwards: {...}, backwards: {...} }}>
  <!-- Page content -->
</div>
```

See `src/pages/index.astro` for examples.

## Rollback

If something goes wrong after deployment:

```bash
git revert <commit-hash>
git push origin main
```

This creates a new commit that undoes the previous one and re-deploys.

